<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-454-534  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 454 534.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 14 1990 v9 n10 p77(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New procedures might gobble up resolution period. (Fedwatch)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   University Systems Inc. (cases)International Data Products Corp. (cases).andO;Topic:     United States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppealsLegal IssuesVendor RelationsProcedures.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>New Procedures Might Gobble Up Resolution PeriodandM;In my April 30 column, I described the new procedure the General ServicesAdministration Board of Contract Appeals uses to determine if a protester isnext in line for award.andM;Only a vendor next in line for award meets the &quot;interested party&quot; definitionfor filing a protest.andP;  The parties involved with that decision have completedtheir analysis and the GSBCA has issued its ruling 10517-P of April 12.andM;After extensive discovery, analysis and evaluation, the GSBCA concluded thatone of the bids between that of the winning vendor, University Systems Inc.,andO;and that of the protester, International Data Products Corp., was responsiveto the solicitation.andP;  Therefore, the GSBCA said, International Data Productsof Gaithersburg, Md., is not an interested party.andM;The board dismissed the protest for lack of standing, even before the companyhad a chance to prove the merits of its protest.andP;  Interestingly, the otherresponsive offer was an alternative bid by University Systems, Milpitas,Calif.andM;In its closing comments, the board seemed to be pleading for help inreversing this idiocy.andP;  The determination of standing in this case requiredlengthy presentations of evidence and arguments by the parties andsignificant work by the government.andM;This preliminary effort alone took most of the 45 days allowed for resolvingprotests.andP;  The resolution of standing in this case may have been more complexthan the protest itself.andM;Although this protest was dismissed, that may not be the result in similarsituations.andP;  What we are faced with is the distinct possibility of doublingthe protest resolution period.andM;And who really needs that?andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>